{
  "topic": "CPU CACHE",
  "icon": "Cpu",
  "scenes": [
    {
      "type": "title",
      "narration": "Your CPU almost never touches RAM. Between the processor and your memory sits a tiny invisible layer \u2014 and it's the real reason computers feel instant.",
      "props": {
        "title": "CPU CACHE",
        "subtitle": "Why your chip barely touches RAM",
        "icon": "Cpu"
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "statement",
      "narration": "Here's the problem: RAM takes 100 nanoseconds to deliver data \u2014 that's 500 idle clock cycles on a modern chip. For a CPU doing billions of operations per second, that's a disaster.",
      "props": {
        "text": "RAM makes your CPU idle for 500 clock cycles",
        "highlight": "500 clock cycles"
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "canvas",
      "narration": "So CPUs have tiered memory baked right onto the chip. L1 cache responds in 1 nanosecond, L2 in 5, L3 in 20. Only on a miss does the request travel all the way to RAM at 100 nanoseconds.",
