    {
      "type": "compare",
      "narration": "A cache hit means the data was already waiting \u2014 instant delivery, CPU never slows. A cache miss means the processor stalls cold, burning hundreds of cycles waiting for RAM to respond.",
      "props": {
        "left": {
          "title": "Cache Hit",
          "icon": "Zap",
          "tone": "heavy",
          "blocks": [
            "Data found in L1",
            "Instant delivery",
            "Zero stall cycles",
            "CPU keeps flying"
          ]
        },
        "right": {
          "title": "Cache Miss",
          "icon": "Clock",
          "tone": "light",
          "blocks": [
            "Data not found",
            "Fetch from RAM",
            "500 cycles lost",
            "CPU stalls cold"
          ]
        }
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "stat",
      "narration": "L1 cache is 100 times faster than RAM. The twist: the entire L1 is only 32 kilobytes \u2014 smaller than a single photo on your phone. Tiny, but it does the heavy lifting.",
      "props": {
        "value": "100\u00d7",
        "label": "L1 cache speed vs RAM"
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "nodes",
      "narration": "Modern CPUs also run a hardware prefetcher. It watches your code's memory patterns and loads data into cache before you even ask \u2014 on sequential loops, it eliminates nearly every miss.",
      "props": {
        "hub": {
          "label": "Prefetcher",
          "icon": "Brain"
        },
        "nodes": [
          {
            "label": "Watches Patterns",
            "icon": "Eye"
          },
          {
            "label": "Loads Ahead",
            "icon": "ArrowRight"
          },
          {
            "label": "Fills Cache",
            "icon": "Zap"
          },
          {
            "label": "Zero Stall",
            "icon": "Timer"
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "statement",
      "narration": "It all works because of locality \u2014 programs reuse the same small chunk of data over and over. Cache bets on that pattern, and wins roughly 95% of the time.",
      "props": {
        "text": "Programs reuse data \u2014 cache wins 95% of the time",
        "highlight": "95%"
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "outro",
      "narration": "That's CPU cache: invisible, the size of a thumbnail, and the real engine behind every fast computer. Follow for one concept like this every single day.",
